 Violent clashes are continuing in Cairo as supporters of the Egyptian President, Hosni Mubarak, lay siege to Tahrir Square, where thousands of anti-government protesters have been demanding he step down immediately. The two sides have been throwing stones and petrol bombs at each other, and fighting with sticks and iron bars. Officials say three people were killed and more than 600 injured. The leading opposition figure, Mohamed ElBaradei, has condemned the attacks on protesters as a criminal act by a criminal regime. He is reported to have called on the army to intervene. The White House has deplored the violence and called for restraint. UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon has said attacks on peaceful demonstrators are unacceptable. The army has called on all protesters to return home and allow Egypt to return to normal. Live page reporters: Aidan Lewis, Joe Boyle, David Gritten, Yaroslav Lukov and Katie Connolly. All times in GMT.
0058 That concludes our live coverage of Egypt&rsquo;s ninth day of anti-government protests, but you can keep up to date with regular news updates throughout the night.
Thank you for following developments on the BBC.
** 0055**
Shereef Abbas tweets: &ldquo;Just the fact that you guys are still tweeting from Tahrir is very comforting to us all.&rdquo;
