Cooper was punched repeatedly and attacked for minutes by a mob of supporters of President Hosni Mubarak on Wednesday. On Thursday, another group of pro-government forces smashed a rock through his car window while he and his crew were in it. Cooper had been reporting from the Cairo streets, but by Thursday night he had gone to ground.
&ldquo;I can&rsquo;t tell you where we are, frankly for our own safety,&rdquo; Cooper said. &ldquo;Systematically, we have seen journalists attacked&hellip;we would like to be showing you instead of&hellip;this strange image of us sitting on the floor of an undisclosed location in dim lighting, we would like to be showing you pictures, live pictures, of what&rsquo;s happening in Liberation Square right now, but we can&rsquo;t do that because our cameras have systematically been taken down through threats, through intimidation, through actual physical attacks.&rdquo;
He continued, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t mind telling you I am a little bit scared, because we frankly don&rsquo;t really know what the next few hours will hold. And I think there&rsquo;s a lot of people who are scared tonight in Egypt.&rdquo;
